Using Data Analysis and Visualization to Explore Spotify's most listened-to songs and determine if the social media outlet "TikTok" had any influence¶

Eric Gorner, Vivek Waghray, Ananya Nadig, Lily Etareri¶

Motivation¶

The 4 of us are avid music listeners. We all have Spotify subscriptions and listen to music on a daily basis. We especially enjoy the "Spotify Wrapped" feature that comes out every year at the beginning of December.¶

This feature provides an easy to read, user friendly rundown of what you listened to over the past year. Among the information included is your most listened-to Artist, most listened-to songs, how much total time you spent listening to music on Spotify, and what genres you listened to. The end product is a Spotify-curated playlist of your top 100 or so songs that you listened to.¶

In the spirit of this feature, we wanted to take a look at the most listened to songs on Spotify as a whole, not just ourselves. We thought this would be very interesting and would be a cool way to get a sense of the music listened to on Spotify. However, in doing this, we wanted to incorporate a twist as well, this twist being the influence social media has on what music we listen to.¶

Over the past couple of years, one platform that rose in popularity was TikTok. This platform allows users to create and post short videos. These videos and their purposes range from comedy to even publicity, with many artists using the platform to promote their music. Something that we are curious about is the influence TikTok had on the music people listened to over the past 2 years. Did one year have more influence over the other?¶

Data Collection and Cleaning¶

Background on Data Sets¶

The data sets that we have selected to use are Data sets from the years 2021 and 2022. There is a data set for both years for TikTok data as well as Spotify data. The data sets that we have collected are from a collection that can be found on both Kaggle and Github. They are all constructed by the same author, so for the most part they are already very clean data sets with matching syntax (a song title that appears in one table will appear exactly the same in another table)¶

Libraries¶

The below libraries are used in order to collect and analyze data. The pandas library is used to create dataframes of the data sets being used, and to then collect values for analysis. The matplotlib library is used to create plots, with sklearn used to create linear regression models¶

2021 Datasets¶

Important Note: The main addition we made to the data sets was a rank variable that gave songs a rank. For Spotify, this number was based on the number of weeks they have spent on Spotify's top 200 chart. For TikTok, which does not release data regarding the number of times a person's sound/song is used in another person's video, this rank is based on the track popularity of the track used in the audio, as well as the artist's popularity behind the audio. This rank variable will provide us with a more accurate song ranking to better rank popular songs on both platforms.¶

Analysis of Song Characteristics for 2021¶

Let's analyze different song characteristics and see if there is any correlation between these features and the songs' ranks

In [12]:
X = spotify_2021['rank'].values.reshape(-1, 1)  
Y = spotify_2021['energy'].values.reshape(-1, 1)
linear_regressor = LinearRegression()
linear_regressor.fit(X, Y)
Y_pred = linear_regressor.predict(X)

plt.scatter(X, Y, s = 10, color = "blue")
plt.plot(X, Y_pred, color='red')
plt.title("Energy vs. rank")
plt.ylabel("energy")
plt.xlabel("rank")
plt.show()

There doesn't seem to be a correlation between enerdy and rank as majority of the songs with high or low energy seem to cluster at the lower ranks. The highest ranked songs are mostly below 0.6 on the energy scale meaning that mid to low energy songs are more likely to be ranked higher.

There is a strong correlation between artist popularity and track popularity. The more popular an artist is on tiktok, the higher the popularity of their tracks. We can see though, that there are outliers, and some artists with higher popularity have tracks that don't perform as well.¶

Of the songs that overlap between TikTok and Spotify's most popular, a lot of the songs cluster in the peak range of 50 and below. This indicates that a lot of songs that are also popular on TikTok are listened to often on Spotify, and thus they have high peaks. However, it's also important to notice that a lot of songs have spent a long time on the charts. Of the songs that cluster in the peak range of 50 and below, most have been on the charts in the realm of 20 to 60 weeks, with many also exceeding 60 weeks on the charts. This time period dates back to over a year ago. This could mean two things. This could mean that some songs that became big on TikTok retained their relevance and are still big, showing that TikTok has been incredibly influential in making songs popular and allowing them to stay popular for a long time. This could also mean that TikTok users are using already popular Spotify songs within their videos. Both are possible conclusions, and a little bit of both is likely true.¶

Conclusion from Hypothesis Testing and Data Analysis¶

Prior to conducting our data analysis, we assumed that 2022 would have a stronger correlation of TikTok's popular songs and Spotify's popular songs than the 2021 year's correlation. According to Statista.com, in 2021, TikTok had approximately 86.9 million users in the United States. The number of users in 2022 reached around 94 million. We had assumed that one of the factors contributing to 2022 having a stronger correlation would be the increase in users. As we see from the analysis conducted above, this assumption seems to not be the case.¶

This could be due to various reasons related to either our experiment conducted, method of data collection, or other reasons. This means we are unable to conclude if the increase in TikTok users from 2021 to 2022 had any positive impact in correlation of popular songs on TikTok to popular songs on Spotify. That being said, in both cases for 2021 and 2022, we did see a correlation between popular songs on TikTok and popular songs on Spotify.¶

Tying back to the original points mentioned at the start:¶

"Something that we are curious about is the influence TikTok had on the music people listened to over the past 2 years. Did one year have more influence over the other?"¶

TikTok does indeed seem to have an influence on music people listen to based on the positive correlation we detected from the data analysis conducted in this project. We are unable to conclude if one year has more influence over the other without looking into additional factors that could contribute to those results.¶
